  <brief_title>A Study of Fluconazole in the Prevention of Fungal Infections in HIV-Infected Patients Living in Areas Where Fungal Infections Are Common</brief_title>
  <official_title>A Double-Blind, Placebo-Controlled Study of Fluconazole in the Prevention of Active Coccidioidomycosis and Other Systemic Fungal Infections in HIV-Infected Patients Living in the Coccidioidal Endemic Area</official_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>Pfizer</agency>
      <agency_class>Industry</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>NIH AIDS Clinical Trials Information Service</source>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      To compare the efficacy of fluconazole versus placebo in preventing the development of active
      coccidioidomycosis and other systemic fungal infections among HIV-infected patients with CD4
      lymphocyte counts &lt; 250 cells/mm3 who are living in the coccidioidal endemic area.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      Patients are randomized to receive either fluconazole or placebo daily.
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
